com.flowpowered.commons.queue

Class SubscribableQueue<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.flowpowered.commons.queue.SubscribableQueue<T>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterable<T>, Collection<T>, Queue<T>

    public class SubscribableQueue<T>
extends Object
implements Queue<T>
    A concurrent queue to which multiple threads can subscribe. Each subscribed thread gets its own copy of the queue, but not of it contents. Items added to the queue (via either add(Object), addAll(java.util.Collection) or offer(Object)) will be added to all the thread queues, but any removal operation is confined to the thread's queue. A thread needs to subscribe to the queue before being able to use it, using subscribe(). The queue to use is selected from the calling thread, using Thread.currentThread(). Once done, a thread should unsubscribe using unsubscribe().
    When a thread constructs a new SubscribableQueue, it can declared itself as the publisher thread, and the operation of the following methods is limited to that thread only: unsubscribeAll(). The following operations operate on all queues if called by the publisher, else on the thread's own queue: add(Object), addAll(java.util.Collection), offer(Object).
    It's possible to add objects for only specific subscribers, as long as they have provided a non-null identifier object when using subscribe(Object), and that the publisher knows which object corresponds to which thread. Calling add(Object, Object), addAll(java.util.Collection, Object) or offer(Object, Object) using a valid identifier will ensure that the object is only passed to the desired subscriber.
    Calls to methods can be expensive because of the cost of Thread.currentThread() on certain platforms. Using mass removal or addition operations (removeAll(java.util.Collection), addAll(java.util.Collection)) is recommended when multiple items need to be removed or added.
